<p>A couple of months ago, I was in Jane Lawâ€™s cozy office. I had taken a great course with her a previous semester, and I wanted to let her to know how much I had enjoyed it. My days in Ithaca were numbered, and I needed closure.</p>

<p>â€œSo, what do you want to do with your life?â€ She asks.</p>

<p>â€œI want to be a designer.â€</p>

<p>â€œOK. What else?â€</p>

<p>As we talked, the shadows in the room become elongated and formless. I realized that while I had studied fairly hard over the past 4 years, I hadnâ€™t done much thinking for myself at all.</p>

<p>She tells me to try going away for a while.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/img/hitching/night.png" alt="Night lights" /></p>

<p>I walk faster now. The pale stucco houses stretch on. Their shadows are long and tangled, and soon they melt into the rest of the night.</p>

<p>I curse myself for my naivety. For thinking that this would be easy.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s dark when I spot a ladder going up the side of an empty office building. I climb up and throw my things in a pile. I crawl into the sleeping bag, and look up into the boundless black blue sky. Far off, the lights of an airplane blink, blink in place.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/img/hitching/danny.png" alt="With Danny in the back up a pickup" /></p>

<p>Who still hitchhikes?</p>

<p>It turns out thereâ€™s a sprawling road subculture. Like any subculture it comes in many flavors that weave and blend together.</p>

<p>I canâ€™t help but feel like a tourist, and thatâ€™s probably what I am. Maybe Iâ€™ll go home afterwards and write a blog post or two about my experience, and then fill it with blurry phone photos.</p>

<p>Danny is something else completely. With the patchwork pants, mutton chops, and crazy â€˜fro, he looks as if he was spit out by a desert hippie commune and then decided not to go home. And that was 2 years ago. He busks to pay the way. Heâ€™s indignant at people who admonish him to â€œget a jobâ€. Heâ€™s nothing but friendly to other travelers.</p>

<p>â€œIâ€™m going to Maine.â€ He says.</p>

<p>â€œWhy?â€</p>

<p>â€œIâ€™m from San Diego originally, and itâ€™s the farthest from San Diego there is.â€</p>

<p>Heâ€™s looking past me now, eyes tinged with the soft orange of dusk.</p>

<p>â€œIâ€™ve tried, but Iâ€™ve never made it. I feel good about this time though.â€</p>

<p><img src="/assets/img/hitching/andrew.png" alt="Andrew buys us burgers at a Wendy's." /></p>

<p>100 miles out of Phoenix, Andrew stops at a Wendyâ€™s to buy us burgers. Heâ€™s been driving for about 2 hours. I am ravenous. I wolf my Son of Baconator down.</p>

<p>Andrew is a Jehovahâ€™s Witness. He made it known at the start. He also made it known that we didnâ€™t have to talk about it. Aware of discomfort that comes with the door-to-door evangelism, heâ€™s simultaneously eager to talk about his faith, and restrained by his own social graces from doing so.</p>

<p>We stop and pick up two more people: an old rancher and a young hitchhiker. He extends the same muted religious enthusiasm to them.</p>

<p>He drops me off at Arizona State University, because I donâ€™t know another landmark in the city. He gives me 5 dollars.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/img/hitching/mishka.png" alt="Mishka was a beautiful dog" /></p>

<p>In the beginning have a web dev gig I carried over from school. Simple web applications that I work on with the McDonaldâ€™s Wifi.</p>

<p>As I hammer away in my editor, huge freight trucks scream past on the highway outside.</p>

<p>Sometimes I take the work to bed. It is very weird and perverse: a guy is lying on his stomach in a sleeping bag staring at a glowing screen next to the highway. A lantern in pitch black. The irony is malicious: I left home to do exactly what I did at home, only without a roof over my head.</p>

